                      <item xml:id="e01">
                        <desc>
                        <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iir #iiv"/> scrawls
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e02">
                        <desc>
                        Psalm 118 contains the spiritual meanings of the Hebrew letters
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e03">
                        <desc>
                          words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#84r #91r #99v #140v #168v"/>, etc.);
                          and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#14r #36r #148v #156v"/>);
                          and in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#148r"/>, line 2);
                          erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#107v #108v #120r #124r"/>, etc.);
                          text has been removed (e.g., <locus target="#17v #108r"/>, )
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e04">
                        <desc>
                          The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line.
                          Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                          appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate
                          script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe
                          completes the line of text above or below the end of the line
                          (throughout). This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of
                          lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#5r #6v #7r #7v"/>)
                        </desc>
                      </item>
                    </list>
                  </additions>
